01:15:09.770 --> 01:15:12.800
Because no matter how much space
you have on your main screen,

01:15:12.830 --> 01:15:16.200
you are always going to want
the widest timeline possible.

01:15:16.200 --> 01:15:19.350
So this screen could be a mile wide,
and I'm still not going to want to keep

01:15:19.350 --> 01:15:22.870
my browsers on here because I'm going
to want this timeline to be really,

01:15:22.870 --> 01:15:23.760
really wide.

01:15:23.760 --> 01:15:26.520
So I take my browser,
shove that off onto the second monitor.

01:15:26.520 --> 01:15:29.770
And if it's as big as a 23-inch monitor,
you've got a lot of space to have

01:15:29.780 --> 01:15:32.760
multiple browser windows open,
view it in icon view and list view,

01:15:32.760 --> 01:15:36.030
and you can stretch them out so you
can see all the metadata and so on.

01:15:36.400 --> 01:15:38.610
And then the third monitor
is for your video out.

01:15:38.660 --> 01:15:41.360
You saw what I talked about in
the beginning with the slides,

01:15:41.360 --> 01:15:42.830
the HD preview of the video out.

01:15:42.860 --> 01:15:44.890
And that works, of course,
with DV as well.

01:15:44.890 --> 01:15:47.000
You can do video out to your DVI monitor.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:48.910
And in this case,
I had it playing full screen

01:15:48.910 --> 01:15:51.310
on this primary screen,
but if you have a second screen,

01:15:51.380 --> 01:15:52.230
it plays out to there.

01:15:52.230 --> 01:15:54.790
So there's your 30-inch with
all your workspace on it,

01:15:54.820 --> 01:15:57.080
your palettes over here,
your video out over here.

01:15:57.080 --> 01:15:59.140
Doesn't that sound like a good way to go?

01:15:59.140 --> 01:16:00.590
We all need one.